y cycling in evaporitic pools; concentration of aldehydes and oxoacids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-assisted C-C bond formation and rearrangement append a two-carbon aldehyde side chain to an imidazole nucleus to give imidazole-4-acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied research specifically names imidazole-4-acetaldehyde as the most important immediate aldehyde precursor and notes that Strecker synthesis from this aldehyde has been proposed. However, a fully demonstrated prebiotic route to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde is not given. This reaction is therefore explicitly speculative but necessary, and it uses the literature-identified feedstocks glyoxylate and formaldehyde within a plausible surface concentration regime. Histidine-specific precursor framing follows the report and the proposed Strecker route of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde noted there; broader mineral-concentration context from Ricardo et al., 2004; Ferris, 2005.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker synthesis of histidine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"neutral to mildly alkaline aqueous setting in evaporitic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldehyde forms imine with ammonia, followed by cyanide addition to give the alpha-aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the strongest histidine-directed reaction in the network. The research explicitly identifies Strecker synthesis of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde as a proposed route to histidine under prebiotic conditions and cites general Strecker chemistry as established for amino acids. Thus this step is literature-aligned, though substrate-specific experimental scope remains limited. Supported by Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1957; and the histidine-precursor route summarized in the supplied report citing the proposed Strecker synthesis of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface phosphoro-Strecker trapping of histidine aminonitrile precursor\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals and montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"near-neutral pH; DAP-mediated phosphoro-Strecker selectivity for aldehydes\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Diamidophosphate captures the Strecker adduct pathway as an N-phosphoroaminonitrile, stabilizing and directing aminonitrile formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied research explicitly highlights phosphoro-Strecker synthesis using DAP with aldehydes and HCN at neutral pH to give N-phosphoroaminonitriles, which are relevant to histidine synthesis if the aldehyde is imidazole-4-acetaldehyde. This is therefore directly literature-guided and one of the best-supported selective surface routes. Supported by Rabinowitz et al./prebiotic phosphoro-Strecker literature as summarized in the report; most directly by Yadav et al., 2020 and related DAP prebiotic phosphorylation studies.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic dephosphorylation to histidine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"variable pH hydrolysis in prebiotic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolytic loss of the phosphoro group converts N-phosphoroaminonitrile to the corresponding free aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature summary explicitly states that N-phosphoroaminonitriles can convert into aminonitriles under varying pH conditions. This reaction therefore follows the reported phosphoro-Strecker scenario closely. Supported by the phosphoro-Strecker literature summarized in the report, including Yadav et al., 2020.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic hydrolysis of histidine aminonitrile to histidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"extended aqueous hydrolysis, geothermal cycling, neutral to mildly alkaline pH\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential nitrile hydration and hydrolysis produce the alpha-amino acid histidine from the aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis to amino acids is standard Strecker chemistry and directly supported by the supplied research. This is a core non-speculative late-stage step once histidine aminonitrile exists. Supported by classic Strecker chemistry and prebiotic aminonitrile studies: Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1957; Commeyras et al., 2004.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic oxidative hydrolysis of histidine aminonitrile to imidazolepyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mixed redox pool chemistry; speculative nonenzymatic conversion\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aminonitrile undergoes hydrolytic/deaminative oxidation netting the corresponding alpha-keto acid, imidazolepyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies imidazolepyruvate as an immediate precursor in a histidine-centered decomposition/biosynthetic framing and separately highlights alpha-ketoacid chemistry as relevant prebiotically. However, a direct prebiotic conversion of histidine aminonitrile to imidazolepyruvate is not experimentally established. This step is therefore explicitly speculative and included only to connect the literature-identified alpha-ketoacid branch. Context from Muchowska et al., 2017; Keller et al., 2014; and the supplied report.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic transamination of imidazolepyruvate to histidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Fe2+-rich pools or mineral interfaces; ketoacid-amination regime\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-ketoacid amination/transamination converts imidazolepyruvate to the corresponding amino acid histidine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step follows the report's emphasis on alpha-ketoacid conversion to amino acids and its explicit identification of imidazolepyruvate as an immediate precursor. While nonenzymatic transamination of this exact substrate is not directly demonstrated in the supplied report, alpha-ketoacid to amino acid chemistry is recognized as a plausible prebiotic bridge between prebiotic and biotic chemistry. Supported broadly by prebiotic transamination literature and the supplied report; e.g., Muchowska et al., 2017; Keller et al., 2014; Foden et al., 2020.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formate to Strecker histidine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction generates formate, which feeds formamide and then HCN-centered surface chemistry, culminating in Strecker synthesis from imidazole-4-acetaldehyde and hydrolysis to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal C1 reduction plus glyoxylate-assisted Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 reduction yields formaldehyde and formate, which converge through glyoxylate and imidazole assembly to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde, followed by Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphoro-Strecker histidine route\",\n      \"description\": \"The imidazole-4-acetaldehyde precursor enters a DAP-mediated phosphoro-Strecker sequence, then dephosphorylation and hydrolysis afford histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Ammonium formate buffered HCN route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal ammonium formate acts as a reservoir feeding formamide-rich chemistry and then the HCN-imidazole-Strecker branch to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct aminonitrile hydrolysis branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Once histidine aminonitrile is generated by Strecker synthesis, direct aqueous hydrolysis in prebiotic pools gives histidine without invoking the alpha-ketoacid branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphoro-Strecker selective aldehyde branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Near-neutral surface conditions selectively trap the imidazole aldehyde in the phosphoro-Strecker manifold before conversion to the free aminonitrile and histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Alpha-ketoacid bridge to histidine\",\n      \"description\": \"Histidine aminonitrile is diverted into an imidazolepyruvate branch, then alpha-ketoacid amination/transamination yields histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate-informed alpha-ketoacid convergence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate production motivates an alpha-ketoacid-rich network; the imidazole branch converges on imidazolepyruvate, which is then aminated to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Glyoxylate-centered surface assembly route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal glyoxylate and formaldehyde converge with imidazole on surface minerals to form imidazole-4-acetaldehyde, then Strecker chemistry yields histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN polymerization to histidine via dual late-stage options\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN oligomerization generates the imidazole core and then the imidazole aldehyde precursor; from there histidine can arise either by direct aminonitrile hydrolysis or through the imidazolepyruvate branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Histidine", "overall_strategy": "This network targets histidine through literature-supported prebiotic frameworks rather than claiming a single fully demonstrated histidine-specific route. The strongest supported core is: (i) hydrothermal generation of small feedstocks such as formate, pyruvate, glyoxylate, formaldehyde and ammonium formate/formamide; (ii) surface HCN-centered chemistry, including HCN oligomerization, cyanosulfidic feedstock generation, Strecker and phosphoro-Strecker formation of imidazole-bearing aminonitrile precursors from imidazole-4-acetaldehyde; and (iii) biochemical/prebiotic hydrolysis and transamination to histidine. Because the literature explicitly states that histidine-specific prebiotic evidence is sparse, the network marks the assembly of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde and imidazolepyruvate as speculative connector steps, but keeps them embedded within documented Strecker, phosphoro-Strecker, HCN polymerization, formamide, alpha-ketoacid, and hydrothermal scenarios. Ten distinct pathways are provided as different valid traversals through the same connected bipartite network.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH5NO2", "iupac_name": "azanium methanoate", "common_name": "ammonium formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2.H3N/c2-1-3;/h1H,(H,2,3);1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "oxoacetic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C2H4N2", "iupac_name": "1H-imidazole", "common_name": "imidazole", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4N2/c1-2-4-3-5-2/h1,3H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H6N2O", "iupac_name": "2-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)ethanal", "common_name": "imidazole-4-acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6N2O/c8-2-1-5-3-6-4-7-5/h2-4H,1H2,(H,6,7)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C6H7N3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanenitrile", "common_name": "histidine aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C6H11N4O3P", "iupac_name": "N-phosphoro-2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanenitrile", "common_name": "N-phosphoro-histidine aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C6H8N2O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxo-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanoic acid", "common_name": "imidazolepyruvic acid", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C6H9N3O2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanoic acid", "common_name": "histidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H9N3O2/c7-5(6(10)11)1-4-2-8-3-9-4/h2-3,5H,1,7H2,(H,8,9)(H,10,11)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C2H4N4", "iupac_name": "2,3-diaminobut-2-enedinitrile", "common_name": "DAMN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4N4/c5-1-3(7)4(8)2-6/h7-8H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "P2H8N4O5", "iupac_name": "diamidophosphate", "common_name": "DAP", "inchi": null, "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by H2 to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents followed by release as formate.", "reasoning": "CO2 reduction to formate on Fe-S minerals is a core hydrothermal prebiotic motif and is specifically aligned with the iron-sulfur/alkaline vent framework used in the histidine precursor network. This step grounds the C1 pool that feeds formamide/ammonium formate chemistry. Supported by hydrothermal vent carbon-fixation analog studies and Fe-S catalysis; used here in the context summarized by Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Cody et al., 2000; Martin & Russell, 2007."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal reduction toward formaldehyde from C1 carbon", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-470K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and elemental iron", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor hydrothermal, reducing conditions; low-yield selective C1 reduction"}, "mechanism": "Sequential hydrogenation of CO2/CO on iron oxide/metal surfaces gives reduced C1 carbonyl products including formaldehyde under Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions.", "reasoning": "Formaldehyde is required by the literature as a relevant precursor for Strecker-type and cyanosulfidic networks. Direct selective hydrothermal formaldehyde formation is not firmly established and remains yield-limited; this is therefore a cautious connector based on Fischer-Tropsch-type hydrothermal chemistry rather than a histidine-specific demonstration. Supported generally by magnetite-catalyzed FTT and hydrothermal organic synthesis studies; speculative in selectivity for formaldehyde. Cited in the broad context of McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2005; Cody et al., 2000."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal formamide generation from formate and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "373-423K", "pressure": "moderate-high", "catalyst": "pyrite and magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic hydrothermal fluid, neutral to alkaline pH; dehydration/condensation in mineral microenvironments"}, "mechanism": "Association of formate with ammonia gives ammonium formate equivalents that dehydrate to formamide in heated mineral-confined systems.", "reasoning": "The supplied literature explicitly identifies formamide as a central prebiotic precursor and notes hydrothermal decomposition/formation relationships involving ammonium formate. This step operationalizes that pool in a mineral-bound hydrothermal setting. Formamide-centered prebiotic synthesis is strongly associated with Saladino and co-workers; hydrothermal relevance summarized in Saladino et al., 2012; Barks et al., 2010."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal ammonium formate formation", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite and greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic vent fluids; salt accumulation in confined pores"}, "mechanism": "Acid-base association of formate/formic acid with ammonia yields ammonium formate as a stable hydrothermal reservoir species.", "reasoning": "The knowledge base specifically identifies ammonium formate as a likely intermediate from HCN/formamide hydrolysis chemistry and a plausible oceanic reservoir feeding amino-acid synthesis. This node improves literature compliance by making that reservoir explicit. Context from Barks et al., 2010; Saladino et al., 2012; Cleaves, 2008."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrothermal C2 oxidation state capture to glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic, Fe2+-rich, hydrothermal carbon-fixation network"}, "mechanism": "Coupling/oxidation-state balancing among C1 intermediates on mineral surfaces yields C2 oxoacid products such as glyoxylate.", "reasoning": "The report identifies glyoxylate as an important prebiotic intermediate linked to metabolic precursor chemistry. Direct hydrothermal formation remains network-level rather than histidine-specific evidence, but glyoxylate scenarios are established in prebiotic systems chemistry. Supported as a plausible connector by Muchowska et al., 2017; Muchowska et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2014."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent/subseafloor redox gradients"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-catalyzed reductive carbon fixation and C-C bond-forming chemistry furnish alpha-keto acids including pyruvate.", "reasoning": "The supplied guidance explicitly lists hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis on magnetite/greigite as a key reaction type, and the literature summary identifies alpha-ketoacid conversion as relevant to amino acid synthesis. Pyruvate is retained as a hub linking hydrothermal and biochemical stages. Supported broadly by Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2017; Keller et al., 2014."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface photochemical HCN generation from formamide/formal C1 nitrogen-carbon pool", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, evaporative concentration, anoxic surface setting"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven decomposition/photochemistry of formamid